DENGUE/DHF UPDATE 2008 (01): BRAZIL
***********************************
A ProMED-mail post
<http://www.promedmail.org>
ProMED-mail is a program of the
International Society for Infectious Diseases
<http://www.isid.org>
In this update, the reports from Brazil include:
[1] Rio Grande do Norte
[2] Rio de Janeiro state
[3] National
******
[1] Rio Grande do Norte
Date: Sun 30 Dec 200
Source: Diario de Natal [in Portuguese, trans. & summ. Mod.TY, edited]
<http://diariodenatal.dnonline.com.br/site/materia.php?idsec=2&idmat=166414>

Children in Rio Grande do Norte were the main victims of DHF,
according to information from the Hospital Infantil Varela Santiago.
According to infectious disease specialist, Kleber Luz, during the
past year [2006] the Hospital Infantil Varela Santiago attended 30
dengue cases counting classical dengue fever and DHF. This year
[2007], that number has practically tripled, reaching 80 [cases].
However, what is more worrying is that this number relates only to
DHF cases. "We have had dengue cases since 1997, with DHF a rarity;
now, we are in this situation [with a high number of DHF cases]. This
is worrying," he said.
Traditionally, the dengue cases increase during the rainy season.
However, currently the city is not receiving a lot of rain [which
ought to be] sufficient to change the occurrence of dengue [cases].
Thus, according to Kleber, it is not necessary to have rains for the
mosquito [populations] to develop. "Where there are people, there are
mosquitoes. Many houses are without [piped] water and the people
[there] store water in tanks and buckets and that is one of the
reasons. Moreover, this city is flooded with construction [projects],
areas propitious for development of [mosquito breeding] foci," he
said.
According to this doctor, since the city is not living through a
dengue epidemic, there is a false feeling that there are no grade 2
[DHF] cases. "It is worse in that there must be a lot of grade 1
[DHF] cases of the disease at home. All these grades are DHF [cases]"
he affirmed.
According to Kleber, the majority of the ill children are from the
interior and are between 3 and 5 years [of age]. "The disease is more
serious in these children," he affirmed.
The only way to avoid dengue is to not let the mosquitoes breed.
Because of this, it is necessary to eliminate their breeding sites
--
Communicated by:
ProMED-PORT
<promed@promedmail.org>
[A map of Brazil showing the location of Rio Grande do Norte and the
city of Natal, as well as the other states. can be located at
